            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Besides these considerations, as also stated by the Authors, SARS-CoV-2 infection is frequently associated with the increase in transaminases and gamma-glutamyl transpeptidase (GGT) serum levels [7, 8] . This is the main bias, potentially leading to the increase in HSI with the consequent overestimation of the prevalence of NAFLD in this population of patients. Nevertheless, the association between NAFLD, increased risk of disease progression and longer viral shedding time could be explained by advanced age, higher BMI and prevalence of comorbidities (e.g. diabetes, arterial hypertension, cardiovascular disease) in the group of patients classified as \"NAFLD\". Indeed, the unfavorable clinical outcome of SARS-CoV-2 infection in more frail patients is wellknown all over the world [9, 10] .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 195,
                    "end": 198,
                    "text": "[7,",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                },
                {
                    "start": 199,
                    "end": 201,
                    "text": "8]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF7"
                },
                {
                    "start": 788,
                    "end": 791,
                    "text": "[9,",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF8"
                },
                {
                    "start": 792,
                    "end": 795,
                    "text": "10]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Overall, the conclusions of this study should be taken with caution and only larger series that include patients with a previous diagnosis of NAFLD before SARS-CoV-2 infection will clarify the clinical outcome of the disease in these patients.",
